The discussion on body image is often dominated by talk of female bodies.
⁣
But what about the way men feel about their bodies? ⁣
⁣
For many men, the pressure to look a certain way is very real, and it is an issue that needs discussing. From unrealistic advertising standards to the rise of social media, the conversation around male body image is growing.⁣
⁣
It's been my experience that my male identifying clients struggle with their body image just as much as any other demographic. However, toxic masculinity, has made it, that much more, challenging for them to speak openly about their struggles and feelings.⁣
⁣
I strive to create a safe space for you to explore concepts like this and break down the barriers that keep you from living your best, authentic life. ⁣
⁣
YOU ARE ART!⁣
⁣
And I am here to help you celebrate that!⁣
⁣
XO #ArtistJessicaRae⁣

𝗠𝗶𝗻𝗱𝗳𝘂𝗹𝗻𝗲𝘀𝘀.⁣
⁣
I could apologize for randomly dropping off social media and for appearing inconsistent, but I won't. I shouldn't have to, and neither should you.⁣
 ⁣
When we made the move away from the #FraserValley  to #ShuswapLake I wanted to challenge myself with taking a step back from social media. I found it was consuming me and not in positive ways.⁣
⁣
So I choose to be mindful ⁣
⁣
When we are focused on the present moment, we are less likely to dwell on the past or worry about the future. This can help us to feel more calm and grounded, and to better handle challenging situations. (And I have had many in 2022 and more await me in 2023)⁣
⁣
Mindfulness can also help to improve our relationships with others. When we are fully present in our interactions with others, we are more likely to listen actively and empathize with them, which can lead to deeper and more meaningful connections.⁣
 ⁣

I invite you into my studio
I encourage you to lean into your vulnerability
You open up. You Share with me.
I reciprocate.

Anyone that has been in my studio and created art with me can attest,
I am an open book.
I wear my heart on my sleeve.
I hold nothing back.

I want to be this way online.
And yet, I hold back.

I have looked to my public silence as armor at times, but in reality, it is just another weight that tries to pull me under.

I want to talk about it, because I truly believe, that in sharing my story, it could become part of someone's survival guide.

You see, we may have more in common than you know.
I am a woman,
I am a mother,
I am a survivor.

12 years and counting

Celebrating self-love is a wonderful way to honor and appreciate yourself. 
Here are some ideas for celebrating self-love:

Practice self-care: Self-care is an important aspect of self-love. Take time to do things that make you feel good, such as taking a relaxing bath, going for a walk in nature, or getting a massage.

Write yourself a love letter: Write down all the things you love about yourself and why. Remind yourself of your strengths, talents, and all the things that make you unique.

Treat yourself: Buy yourself something special, such as a new outfit, a book you've been wanting to read, or a favorite treat. You deserve to treat yourself to things that bring you joy.

Spend time alone: Take time to be alone with yourself and do things that make you happy. This can be anything from reading a book to watching a movie, or simply sitting quietly and reflecting.

Practice gratitude: Take time to appreciate all the things you have in your life, and be grateful for them. This can help shift your focus from negative thoughts to positive ones, and help you feel more positive and happy.

Do something creative: Explore your creative side by doing something you enjoy, such as painting, drawing, or writing. Creativity can be a great way to express yourself and feel good about your abilities.

Remember that self-love is an ongoing process, and it's important to continue to practice self-love regularly. Celebrating self-love is a great way to start!

Self Portraits 
This photo took me aback when I first saw it.

In some ways, I do not even recognize myself.
The woman in this photo is tired. Exhausted, rather.
The weight, she carries upon her shoulders and heart is evident.

This is not the smiley, bubbly woman most know and see day to day.

This is a photograph of a Mother.

A Mother, no matter how tired, no matter how tortured, will continue to persevere and advocate for her children.

It's funny, in a way, that I hardly recognized her, as I know her so well.

I see her. I hold space for her. 

She is not alone. She has a village behind her.

She is me and I am her.

This is the thing about art and play - it can be very cathartic and therapeutic.

Hi Friends

For those new to my feed, welcome! I thought I would take this opportunity to (re)introduce myself.

My name is Jessica Rae, and I am an Intimate Portrait Artist (photographer)

What is an Intimate Portrait Artist, you ask?

An intimate portrait artist is a type of visual artist who specializes in creating portraits that reveal the unique and personal characteristics of their subjects. They aim to capture the essence of a person's character, emotions, and individuality in a way that is authentic and honest.

Unlike traditional portrait artists who may focus on creating a visually accurate representation of their subjects, (or one that is considered "beautiful" by societies skewed perceptions)  intimate portrait artists often go beyond surface-level appearances to create a deeper and more personal connection between the viewer and the subject. They strive to capture the subject's personality and emotions in a way that is both revealing and captivating.

Who is Jessica Rae beyond that?

I am a mother, a partner, and a ride or die friend.
I was born and raised in the Fraser Valley of BC, Canada (near Vancouver, BC)
I recently fell in love with and relocated to Salmon Arm, BC. 
A small, but beautiful city along the Shuswap Lake.

I am about to celebrate 10 years with Mr. Jessica Rae (as he is affectionately known) Together we have 2 dogs, 3 cats and 5 human offspring.

I fucking love Alpacas !!! (and, I cuss a lot)

I have been an artist for as long as I can recall. Dabbling in Drawing, Painting, Woodwork, Written Word, Musical Composition, the list goes on = ARTIST

I am driven with a purpose to utilize my art to help people tell their story, because you never know how one sentence of your life story could inspire someone to rewrite their own, or become part of their survival guide. 

Art is : Cathartic - Healing - Transformative

Art is supposed to be a medium for self-expression and should not be restrained by censorship. It should be allowed to exist in its purest form, without any limitations. 

This not only restricts the artist's freedom but also deprives the audience of experiencing the full range of emotions and perspectives that the art has to offer. It's important to remember that art is subjective, and what may offend one person may not offend another.

Let's work towards creating a more open-minded and accepting society where artists can express themselves freely and where their work can be appreciated for what it truly is - a reflection of their unique vision and perspective.

Now, I want to talk about the importance of having a good makeup artist as a photographer.

A good makeup artist can make all the difference in bringing a vision to life. They can help create the desired mood or tone, highlight your clients favourite features, and ensure that the overall look is polished and professional.

Overall, a good makeup artist is an invaluable part of any successful photo session. So if you're a photographer, don't underestimate the impact that a talented makeup artist can have on the final product. Trust me, it's worth the investment!

It's time to focus on YOU! 💫⁣⁣

We often focus on improving our external selves, but what about our inner selves? Taking the time to do inner self work can be a powerful tool for personal growth and healing. Here are a few reasons why I believe inner self work is important and good:

Self-awareness: When we take the time to reflect on our thoughts, feelings, and behaviors, we become more self-aware. This self-awareness can help us identify patterns and habits that may be holding us back, allowing us to make positive changes in our lives.

Healing: Inner self work can be a powerful tool for healing past wounds and traumas. By exploring our emotions and experiences, we can gain a deeper understanding of ourselves and work through any unresolved issues.

Empowerment: When we do inner self work, we take ownership of our lives and our choices. We become empowered to make positive changes and create the life we want.

So, take some time out for yourself today, and focus on your inner self. Whether it's journaling, meditating, or talking to a therapist, investing in your inner self is always worth it. 

It's okay to not have everything figured out. Take small steps, be kind to yourself, and always remember that you are doing the best you can. ⁣⁣✨💛

MOVEMENT 💕

I want to take a moment to talk about the amazing benefits of connecting with your body through movement.  Whether it's dancing, yoga, or just going for a walk, taking the time to move your body and focus on the sensations can do wonders for your physical and mental well-being.

In a world that often encourages us to be disconnected from our bodies and live in our heads, it can be easy to forget how important it is to check in with ourselves on a deeper level. But when we take the time to move our bodies and really feel into our muscles, our breath, and our heartbeat, we can gain a new sense of clarity and self-awareness.

So if you're feeling stressed, overwhelmed, or just in need of some grounding, I encourage you to try moving your body in a way that feels good to you. It doesn't have to be anything fancy or complicated - just take a few deep breaths and start to notice how your body wants to move.

Today, I challenge you to take some time to move your body. Whether it's a gentle yoga flow, a run in the park, or simply dancing around your living room, take a few moments to connect with your body and appreciate all that it does for you. Your mind and body will thank you! ❤️🙏

HOT TIP: This is also great practice for your upcoming Intimate Portrait Session. I strive to create a collaborative Art Experience by having you move and connect with your body in ways that feel good to you. 🥰

Grief is a journey that we all have to take at some point in our lives. It is the natural response to loss, whether it's the loss of a loved one, a job, a relationship, or a dream. It can be a painful and overwhelming experience, but it's important to remember that it's okay to grieve.

Grief is not a one-size-fits-all experience. Everyone experiences it differently, and there's no right or wrong way to grieve. Some people may feel sadness, anger, guilt, or even relief. It's important to honor your own feelings and not compare them to others.

It's also important to take care of yourself during this time. Grief can be exhausting, both emotionally and physically. Be gentle with yourself and allow yourself to rest when you need it. Reach out to friends, family, or a professional if you need support.

Remember that grief is not a linear process. It's normal to have good days and bad days, and there may be times when you feel like you've taken two steps forward and one step back. Be patient with yourself and trust that healing takes time.

If you're grieving right now, know that you're not alone. It's okay to feel what you're feeling, and there are people who care about you and want to support you. Sending love and strength to anyone who is navigating through grief.

Mamas for Mamas is a beacon of hope, a specialized poverty relief agency, and an all-inclusive community for mothers and caregivers. Their vision is one we hold close to our hearts: a future where no mama or child is left behind. Through their dedication, they've shown that unity and compassion can create real change.
